{
  "text": "Geographical distance between sex-sorting facility and IVEP laboratories may be a limitation to the expansion of RSS in commercial programs. However, there is the potential to use re-frozen of RSS. Research shows that the RSS can be re-frozen without losing functional viability, including reports of births of lambs after IVEP and/or ET [CITATION_1] and after AI [CITATION_2] . In bovines, the birth of a calf after AI with frozen-thawed, sex-sorted, and re-frozen-thawed sperm was also reported [CITATION_3] . However, Underwood, et al. [CITATION_4] reported decreased motility, feasibility, and speed of sperm when sperm were exposed a new freezing procedure. The possibility of re-freezing RSS without losing their fertilization ability might overcome the limitation of distance between the sorting and IVEP embryo laboratories.",
  "citation_candidates": [
